  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The command not to go into a house of mourning (מרזח, loud crying, cry of lament for one dead, see on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Amos 6:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), not to show sympathy with the survivors, is explained by the Lord in the fearfully solemn saying: I withdraw from this people my peace, grace, and mercy. שׁלום is not \"the inviolateness of the relation between me and my people\" (Graf), but the pace of God which rested on Judah, the source of its well-being, of its life and prosperity, and which showed itself to the sinful race in the extension to them of grace and mercy. The consequence of the withdrawal of this peace is the death of great and small in such multitudes that they can neither be buried nor mourned for (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 16:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). התגּדד, but one's self, is used in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 14:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " for נתן שׂרט, to make cuts in the body, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 19:28",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; and קרח, Niph., to crop one's self bald, acc. to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 14:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", to shave a bare place on the front part of the head above the eyes. These are two modes of expressing passionate mourning for the dead which were forbidden to the Israelites in the law, yet which remained in use among the people, see on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 19:28",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 14:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". להם, for them, in honour of the dead.",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
